subsection.p:
Consider the quadratic equation y = 2(x - 3)^2 - 8 By expanding the squared expression and collecting like terms, we can rewrite the equation in standard form as \begin{aligned}[t] y \amp= 2(x^2 - 6x + 9) - 8\\ y \amp = 2x^2 - 12x + 10 \end{aligned}
The vertex of this parabola is \begin{aligned}[t] x_v \amp= \frac{-(-12)}{2(2)}=3\\ y_v \amp = 2(3)^2 - 12(3) + 10=-8 \end{aligned}
and its graph is shown below.

Notice that the coordinates of the vertex, (3,-8), are apparent in the original equation; we don’t need to do any computation to find the vertex.
	\begin{alignedat}{2}
		y = 2(x - \amp \alert{3})^2 ~ \amp\alert{- 8}\\
		\amp \alert{x_v} \amp \alert{y_v}
		\end{alignedat}

This equation is an example of the vertex formvertex form for a quadratic function.

